\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\i Introduces\i0 \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\ql\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 	Staves and Systems\line 	Clefs and Time Signatures\line 	Notes, Rests and Bar lines\line 	Beams and Ties\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Let's begin by entering an extract from a three-part sonata by G.P. Cima, published in 1610. This will give you the opportunity to familiarize yourself with the basic operations of Calliope. In this lesson we shall introduce notes, rests, barlines, clefs, time signatures and ties.  At the end of the lesson the example will look like this:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_24.eps \width8500\height6840
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Philosophy\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Calliope is organized with the assumption that you have a clear idea of what you are going to be doing with the notation ± in other words, that you are working from some pre-existing notation (facsimile edition, published score, manuscript, etc.) and have a page design already in mind. While it is always possible to change your design decisions at any time, you will find it easier to work according to a pre-determined plan. It is thus best to think about such things as prefatory material, page layout, staff sizes, etc., at the start of work. In these examples, we will be using a straightforward organisation based on Calliope's built-in default styles and proportions, but as you become familiar with Calliope and see how it accommodates the kinds of music you produce, you will develop ways of working with the program which best suit your needs.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 When using Calliope you need to be aware of the \i meaning\i0  of the music, not just its appearance on the page.  For example, if you want to notate a triplet rhythm, the way this usually appears is as a bracket and a 3 above a group of three notes.  However, it would be a mistake to simply put the appropriate graphic symbols together as you might with a drawing program: that is, a conventional arrangement of three notes, a bracket, and the digit `3'. Instead, Calliope provides a Tuple Tool, which will register the specified notes as a triplet (or some other desired timed note group) and display it accordingly.  More importantly, Calliope will ensure that the triplet timing is observed when the music is formatted automatically and when it is played back over a sound system.  Therefore, it is important to learn which tools Calliope makes available for implementing the \i meaning\i0  of your music.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 There is also a major philosophical difference between Calliope and most other notation programs. Other systems often offer note entry by means of a scrolling system which extends an indefinite distance to the right ± a pseudo-page of infinite width, one system tall; the making of pages of music is a separate operation.  This `wait-until-later' method of page layout was a necessary workaround for underpowered computers (and perhaps under-optimized programs). The combination of Calliope and NextStep provides sufficient computing power to make the separation of entry/editing and page making unnecessary; in addition, Calliope treats the page as a more fundamental unit, one which has a more dynamic existence. Calliope automatically calculates where new pages begin based on what is there, as a word processor program does. Systems having differing numbers of staves may appear in the same document.  Also, page headers and footers (running titles) are associated with systems, so that the running titles are seen on the correct page, wherever the system happens to placed.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Starting out\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Start up Calliope by double-clicking on its icon; in a few moments the basic menu and the  Tools panel will be visible.  The Tools Panel looks like this:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_23.eps \width5640\height8500
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\ql\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 During this lesson you will use some of these tools.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0  First, click \fs24\f1\b0\i0 N\f1 ew...\f0  from the \fs24\f1\b0\i0 D\f1 ocument\f0  menu, and the following panel will appear:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_22.tiff \width2000\height3180
}¬} \par
